When x is less than or equal
to 0, f is 1 minus 2 sine of x.

00:00:10.790 --> 00:00:15.920
When x is greater than 0,
f is e to the negative 4x.

00:00:15.920 --> 00:00:19.570
Show that f is
continuous at x equals 0.

00:00:19.570 --> 00:00:21.770
So for something to be
continuous at x equals 0,

00:00:21.770 --> 00:00:23.730
let's think about
what has to happen.

00:00:23.730 --> 00:00:27.570
So if I have a function
here-- So that is my x-axis.

00:00:27.570 --> 00:00:31.710
And let's say this is my y-axis.

00:00:31.710 --> 00:00:33.790
And we care about what
happens at x equals 0.

00:00:33.790 --> 00:00:35.690
So x equals 0 there.

00:00:35.690 --> 00:00:39.220
And let's say that
this is our function.

00:00:39.220 --> 00:00:42.009
So maybe our function maybe
looks something like this.

